                        "content": "A client has received an unsealed radioactive isotope for treatment of thyroid cancer. Which instruction is essential for the nurse to provide the client?",
                        "subjectId": "ad5ab04c79144c0ea9b83385308c3b1d",
                        "difficultyIds": "80db17ea97ed8fdcd1b6b9666390fca1",
                        "difficulty": "考试范围-Applying 应用",
                        "textAnalysis": "Rationale:\nBodily fluids contain the radioactive material, so others needs to be shielded from possible exposure. Clients would at best have a dedicated toilet for use during the first 2 weeks and need to also flush 3 times after use. Some radioactivity will be in the saliva for about the first week, so during this time fruits with cores that will become contaminated need to be avoided. Disposable eating utensils would also be used during this period of time. Contact with pregnant women, infants, and children is avoided for the first week and then a distance of 3 feet (1 meter) or more needs to be maintained, and exposure would be limited to 1 hour per day.\nTest-Taking Strategy:\nFocus on the subject, teaching for a client who has received an unsealed radioactive isotope. Note the strategic word, essential. Review each option to determine whether there is the potential for contamination with the client's bodily fluids. Then consider the options that have time frames, and determine whether they are realistic. This will direct you to option 1.",
                        "id": "45bc1a00a7f64b37b3379c772af2d30a",
                        "mark": "0",
                        "collectionState": "0"
                    },
                    {
                        "optionList": [
